#. (itstool) path: chapter/title
#: xml/vt_introduction.xml:10
msgid "Virtualization Technology"
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: abstract/para
#: xml/vt_introduction.xml:17
msgid ""
"Virtualization is a technology that provides a way for a machine (Host) to "
"run another operating system (guest virtual machines) on top of the host "
"operating system."
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: sect1/title
#: xml/vt_introduction.xml:25
msgid "Overview"
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: sect1/para
#: xml/vt_introduction.xml:29
msgid ""
"<phrase role=\"productname\"><phrase os=\"osuse\">openSUSE Leap</"
"phrase><phrase os=\"sles\">SUSE Linux Enterprise Server</phrase><phrase os="
"\"sled\">SUSE Linux Enterprise Desktop</phrase></phrase> includes the latest "
"open source virtualization technologies, Xen and KVM. With these "
"hypervisors, <phrase role=\"productname\"><phrase os=\"osuse\">openSUSE "
"Leap</phrase><phrase os=\"sles\">SUSE Linux Enterprise Server</"
"phrase><phrase os=\"sled\">SUSE Linux Enterprise Desktop</phrase></phrase> "
"can be used to provision, de-provision, install, monitor and manage multiple "
"virtual machines (VM Guests) on a single physical system (for more "
"information see <xref linkend=\"gloss.vt.hypervisor\"/>)."
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: sect1/para
#: xml/vt_introduction.xml:36
msgid ""
"Out of the box, <phrase role=\"productname\"><phrase os=\"osuse\">openSUSE "
"Leap</phrase><phrase os=\"sles\">SUSE Linux Enterprise Server</"
"phrase><phrase os=\"sled\">SUSE Linux Enterprise Desktop</phrase></phrase> "
"can create virtual machines running both modified, highly tuned, "
"paravirtualized operating systems and fully virtualized unmodified operating "
"systems. Full virtualization allows the guest OS to run unmodified and "
"requires the presence of AMD64/Intel 64 processors which support either "
"Intel* Virtualization Technology (Intel VT) or AMD* Virtualization (AMD-V)."
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: sect1/para
#: xml/vt_introduction.xml:45
msgid ""
"The primary component of the operating system that enables virtualization is "
"a hypervisor (or virtual machine manager), which is a layer of software that "
"runs directly on server hardware. It controls platform resources, sharing "
"them among multiple VM Guests and their operating systems by presenting "
"virtualized hardware interfaces to each VM Guest."
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: sect1/para
#: xml/vt_introduction.xml:53
msgid ""
"<phrase os=\"sles;sled\">SUSE Linux Enterprise is an enterprise-class</"
"phrase><phrase os=\"osuse\">openSUSE is a</phrase> Linux server operating "
"system that offers two types of hypervisors: Xen and KVM. Both hypervisors "
"support virtualization on the AMD64/Intel 64 architecture. For the POWER "
"architecture, KVM is supported. Both Xen and KVM support full virtualization "
"mode. In addition, Xen supports paravirtualized mode. <phrase role="
"\"productname\"><phrase os=\"osuse\">openSUSE Leap</phrase><phrase os=\"sles"
"\">SUSE Linux Enterprise Server</phrase><phrase os=\"sled\">SUSE Linux "
"Enterprise Desktop</phrase></phrase> with Xen or KVM acts as a "
"virtualization host server (<xref linkend=\"gloss.vt.vhs\"/>) that supports "
"VM Guests with its own guest operating systems. The SUSE VM Guest "
"architecture consists of a hypervisor and management components that "
"constitute the VHS, which runs many application-hosting VM Guests."
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: sect1/para
#: xml/vt_introduction.xml:68
msgid ""
"In Xen, the management components run in a privileged VM Guest often called "
"<xref linkend=\"gloss.vt.dom0\"/>. In KVM, where the Linux kernel acts as "
"the hypervisor, the management components run directly on the VHS."
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: sect1/title
#: xml/vt_introduction.xml:75
msgid "Virtualization Capabilities"
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: sect1/para
#: xml/vt_introduction.xml:77
msgid ""
"Virtualization design provides many capabilities to your organization. "
"Virtualization of operating systems is used in many computing areas:"
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: listitem/para
#: xml/vt_introduction.xml:85
msgid ""
"Server consolidation: Many servers can be replaced by one big physical "
"server, so hardware is consolidated, and Guest Operating Systems are "
"converted to virtual machine. It provides the ability to run legacy software "
"on new hardware."
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: listitem/para
#: xml/vt_introduction.xml:93
msgid ""
"Isolation: guest operating system can be fully isolated from the Host "
"running it. So if the virtual machine is corrupted, the Host system is not "
"harmed."
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: listitem/para
#: xml/vt_introduction.xml:100
msgid ""
"Migration: A process to move a running virtual machine to another physical "
"machine. Live migration is an extended feature that allows this move without "
"disconnection of the client or the application."
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: listitem/para
#: xml/vt_introduction.xml:107
msgid ""
"Disaster recovery: <xref linkend=\"gloss.vt.virtualized\"/> guests are less "
"dependent on the hardware, and the Host server provides snapshot features to "
"be able to restore a known running system without any corruption."
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: listitem/para
#: xml/vt_introduction.xml:115
msgid ""
"Dynamic load balancing: A migration feature that brings a simple way to load-"
"balance your service across your infrastructure."
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: sect1/title
#: xml/vt_introduction.xml:123
msgid "Virtualization Benefits"
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: sect1/para
#: xml/vt_introduction.xml:125
msgid ""
"Virtualization brings a lot of advantages while providing the same service "
"as a hardware server."
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: sect1/para
#: xml/vt_introduction.xml:130
msgid ""
"First, it reduces the cost of your infrastructure. Servers are mainly used "
"to provide a service to a customer, and a virtualized operating system can "
"provide the same service, with:"
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: listitem/para
#: xml/vt_introduction.xml:138
msgid ""
"Less hardware: You can run several operating system on one host, so all "
"hardware maintenance will be reduced."
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: listitem/para
#: xml/vt_introduction.xml:144
msgid ""
"Less power/cooling: Less hardware means you do not need to invest more in "
"electric power, backup power, and cooling if you need more service."
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: listitem/para
#: xml/vt_introduction.xml:150
msgid ""
"Save space: Your data center space will be saved because you do not need "
"more hardware servers (less servers than service running)."
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: listitem/para
#: xml/vt_introduction.xml:156
msgid ""
"Less management: Using a VM Guest simplifies the administration of your "
"infrastructure."
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: listitem/para
#: xml/vt_introduction.xml:162
msgid ""
"Agility and productivity: Virtualization provides <emphasis>migration</"
"emphasis> capabilities, <emphasis>live migration</emphasis> and "
"<emphasis>snapshots</emphasis>. These features reduce downtime, and bring an "
"easy way to move your service from one place to another without any service "
"interruption."
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: sect1/title
#: xml/vt_introduction.xml:173
msgid "Virtualization Modes"
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: sect1/para
#: xml/vt_introduction.xml:175
msgid ""
"Guest operating systems are hosted on virtual machines in either full "
"virtualization (FV) mode or paravirtual (PV) mode. Each virtualization mode "
"has advantages and disadvantages."
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: listitem/para
#: xml/vt_introduction.xml:183
msgid ""
"Full virtualization mode lets virtual machines run unmodified operating "
"systems, such as Windows* Server 2003. It can use either Binary Translation "
"or <xref linkend=\"gloss.vt.hwassisted\"/> virtualization technology, such "
"as AMD* Virtualization or Intel* Virtualization Technology. Using hardware "
"assistance allows for better performance on processors that support it."
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: listitem/para
#: xml/vt_introduction.xml:191
msgid ""
"Some guest operating systems hosted in full virtualization mode can be "
"configured to use drivers from the SUSE Virtual Machine Drivers Pack (VMDP) "
"instead of drivers originating from the operating system. Running virtual "
"machine drivers improves performance dramatically on guest operating "
"systems, such as Windows Server 2003. For more information, see <xref "
"linkend=\"app.vmdp.driver\" xrefstyle=\"ChapTitleOnPage\"/>."
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: listitem/para
#: xml/vt_introduction.xml:202
msgid ""
"To be able to run under paravirtual mode, guest operating systems usually "
"need to be modified for the virtualization environment. However, operating "
"systems running in paravirtual mode have better performance than those "
"running under full virtualization."
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: listitem/para
#: xml/vt_introduction.xml:208
msgid ""
"Operating systems currently modified to run in paravirtual mode are called "
"<emphasis>paravirtualized operating systems</emphasis> and include <phrase "
"role=\"productname\"><phrase os=\"osuse\">openSUSE Leap</phrase><phrase os="
"\"sles\">SUSE Linux Enterprise Server</phrase><phrase os=\"sled\">SUSE Linux "
"Enterprise Desktop</phrase></phrase> and NetWare® 6.5 SP8."
msgstr ""
